  "opinion": "As a hairdresser in Los Angeles with a vocational diploma and a family of three, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people’s experiences—especially in fields where assumptions about ability often lead to self-doubt. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just an academic concept; it’s the quiet pressure many feel when they’re told they’re ‘not good at math’ or ‘not the type to succeed in science.’ For me, this plays out daily in my salon: clients who’ve been told they’re ‘not artistic’ often avoid creative projects, and that mindset can bleed into other areas of life. In STEM, it’s similar—when students internalize the idea that their gender or background makes them less capable, their performance suffers. But here’s the thing: we don’t need to fix STEM from the top down. Instead, we should start by listening. My parents, both educated, taught me that talent isn’t fixed—it’s built through practice and support. So, addressing stereotype threat means creating spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes without judgment. At my salon, I’ve seen this work: when clients feel heard, they’re more likely to try new techniques. In STEM, it means teachers and mentors who acknowledge that everyone starts somewhere and that effort matters more than innate ability. We shouldn’t be trying to erase stereotypes but to reframe them—showing that success in science or math isn’t about being ‘special’ but about having the curiosity and resilience to keep going. This is something we can do in our communities, starting with small conversations and celebrating the progress of underrepresented groups. It’s not about fixing people; it’s about fixing the narrative that holds them back.",
